                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51 W 89France/297: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-05-06T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 6, 1926—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 6—2:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>178. After sending my 173, May 5th, I met Briand,<note n="3" xml:id="d58fn3"
                        >Aristide Briand, French President of the Council and Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> who, without any remark on my part, raised this very point
                    that prior ratification by us would facilitate his task and said that in view of
                    the ratification of the other agreements he hoped our Senate would act quickly
                    on the French one.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
